Title: Linking forum posts -rprog-003-4-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Diferencia entre elapsed time y user time.
Input.posts:
Buenas compañer@s, ¿A qué hace referencia cada uno? gracias de antemano ;)
Upvotes:
0
El elapsed time es el tiempo que pasa entre que el usuario da un input al programa y recibe una respuesta. El user time es el tiempo que pasa la CPU computando el código Normalmente son parecidos, excepto en algunos casos (que se explican en el vídeo) Al menos así lo he entendido yo ;)
Upvotes:
1
Gracias Oliver, Con respecto a tu respuesta me surge una duda: Línea ROJA equivale a ELAPSED TIME. Línea VERDE equivale a USER TIME. Tiempo 1) Si tu envías un input, el tiempo empieza a contar. Habrá un pequeño tiempo entre que envías el input y la CPU comienza a calcular (en el gráfico sería desde que le das el input en rojo, hasta que comienza el tiempo CPU en verde). Tiempo 2) El propio tiempo de cÁlculo en la CPU (línea verde completa). Tiempo 3) Desde final del tiempo de cálculo en CPU hasta que recibes la respuesta en pantalla (final línea roja). Pensándolo así, se podría dar el caso: ELAPSED TIME < USER TIME ? Este razonamiento no puede ser válido según la propia teoría del curso, alguna sugerencia o alguien que pueda aclararlo. Un saludo y gracias de nuevo.
Upvotes:
1
Hola Eduardo, Por lo que entendí, el caso elapsed.time < user.time puede darse si tenés más de una CPU o core, y el código está optimizado para poder utilizar el procesamiento paralelo (slide 6 de R Profiler part 1). El código de ejemplo está en la slide 7 (aunque los tiempos dependerán muchísimo del hardware que tengas, yo no he sido capaz de emular el comportamiento en mi laptop)
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Para poder emularlo tienes que utilizar un paquete que utilice programación en paralelo. En general R es 'single threaded' por lo que no utilizará sino una CPU. Esa es una de las diferencias principales con Revolution Analytics, la versión de pago de R. Los paquetes que utilizan programación en paralelo no son tantos en la version gratuita y en general están todavía en desarrollo.

Input.threadtitle: Resources to freshen up mathematics skills? Last lecture flew over my head.
Input.posts:
Hey, so my math background is very limited and multiple times during the lectures of week 4 I got a little lost. Is there a good resource to update my math knowledge so that this will not be a consistent problem? Or alternatively, what topic in mathematics would these things fall under just so I could try to google resources myself. Some example things that I would in interested getting a resource about: logs,regressions,what the greek symbols represent, anything that wouldn't be covered in the first half of high school but would in these lectures. Edit: Good list of stat videos that look promising : https://www.khanacademy.org/math/probability/descriptive-statistics if anyone has some reading material suggestions though that would be great
Upvotes:
12
Some of the examples in week 4's lecture were talking about linear regression and advanced matrix operations, but we're not expected to know what they are yet. I've studied linear regression before, and you will learn it in a later class in the specialization. Dr. Peng was just using those data for examples of how to apply Simulation, but we won't be doing any simulation or linear regression for the quiz/programming assignment. Basically what you were supposed to take away from the lecture is that there are a bunch of functions that can generate random numbers in some specific patterns (normal distribution fitting randoms, and others). We'll learn about what the normal distribution actually is in another class. Same goes for the greek letters..
Upvotes:
1
Same case with me as well. I was very good at Maths 20 years ago, not sure how much I can remember now. Can you please help/guide me to find tutorials/books/web sites to refresh my Maths level that is required for Datascience specialization track [Statistical inference and Regression models] Thanks in advance.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The Resources page of the Data Science Specialization wiki contains references to suitable learning resources.

Input.threadtitle: How to pass arguments to model fitting functions
Input.posts:
I would like to create a function to fit several logistic regression models using the lrm function in the rms package. I'm having trouble making the function substitute the name of the response variable as the outcome in the formula. How do I build the formula properly to make it evaluate it and run the model? thanks. require(rms) out.lrm <- function(outcome){ # lrm is function used to fit logistic regression models; f1 <- lrm(outcome ~ x1 + x3 + x7 + x11 + x16, data=ds1, x=TRUE, y=TRUE) f1 anova(f1) plot(summary(f1), log=TRUE, main=paste('Log-odds', outcome, sep=' ')) v1 <- validate(f1, B=150) v1 } #Repeat function on several outcomes (once it works) out.lrm(z7) #out.lrm(z43) #out.lrm(z25) #out.lrm(z71) When I run the function on the first outcome, I get an error that: Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos) : object 'z7' not found. thanks for any help you might provide.

Input.threadtitle: Quiz Week 4:Need clarification: better understanding on Generating Random Numbers
Input.posts:
Question 4 It is my understanding Probability distribution functions usually have four functions associated with them. The functions are prefixed with a d for density r for random number generation p for cumulative distribution q for quantile function As a result, ppois for Probability distribution functions beginning with the `p' prefix are used to evaluate the cumulative distribution function. Please clarify the explanation below ============================================================ Which function can be used to evaluate the inverse cumulative distribution function for the Poisson distribution? Your Answer Score Explanation qpois dpois ppois Inorrect 0.00 Probability distribution functions beginning with the `q' prefix are used to evaluate the cumulative distribution function. rpois Total 0.00 / 1.00
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
For a random variable $$X$$, function p...(x) will return the probability $$p$$ that $$X \le x$$. A quantile function q...(p) will return the value of $$x$$ such that the probability that $$X \le x$$ is $$p$$. Thus, a quantile function is the inverse function of a cumulative probability function.
Instructor's post : For a random variable $$X$$, function p...(x) will return the probability $$p$$ that $$X \le x$$. A quantile function q...(p) will return the value of $$x$$ such that the probability that $$X \le x$$ is $$p$$. Thus, a quantile function is the inverse function of a cumulative probability function.
